+
+## 11. Where to make the same change in the real application
+
+If you want your custom tool to become part of the actual CLI rather than just a script-local experiment, the current extension point is code-level registration.
+
+### Option A: private/local registration
+
+If you control the session-building code, append your tool to the tool list after calling `get_all_tools(...)` and before constructing `NativeExecutor`.
+
+That pattern matches how `SessionBuilder` already composes skills, deferred tools, MCP wrappers, and core tools.
+
+### Option B: built-in native tool
+
+To make it a true built-in tool in this snapshot, update `duh.tools.registry.get_all_tools()` so it imports and appends your tool class in the same style as `TaskTool`, `HTTPTool`, or `TodoWriteTool`.
+
+That is the real “registration” path today.
+
+### Option C: expose it to the model in a session-local harness
+
+If you are building an integration test, benchmark, or alternative runner, you can skip the global registry and just pass your tool object in:
+
+- to `NativeExecutor(tools=[...])`
+- to `EngineConfig(tools=[...])`
+- or to `query(..., tools=[...])`
+
+That is often the fastest path when prototyping.
+
+---
+
+## 12. Common mistakes when adding a tool
+
+### Mistake 1: inventing a plugin API that does not exist
+
+This checkout does support deferred tools and plugin-discovered metadata for `ToolSearch`, but the core native runtime still works on concrete Python objects in a tool list. If you are adding a new built-in tool, you need a class and a registry entry, not just a manifest.
+
+### Mistake 2: returning plain strings from `call(...)`
+
+Built-in tools return `ToolResult`, and `NativeExecutor.run(...)` is designed around that. Keep your tool implementation aligned with the `Tool` protocol.
+
+### Mistake 3: skipping schema validation
+
+The model only knows how to call tools because their `input_schema` is exposed upstream. Bad schemas cause downstream failures that are much harder to debug than calling `validate_tool_schema(...)` once.
+
+### Mistake 4: coupling approval to rendering
+
+Approval belongs either in `tool.check_permissions(...)` or `Deps.approve`, not in the renderer and not in the provider.
+
+### Mistake 5: trying to test tool invocation with `StubProvider`
+
+`StubProvider` is excellent for smoke testing the CLI and event plumbing, but it does not emit tool-use blocks. Use `NativeExecutor.run(...)` or a tiny provider stub that yields `assistant` messages containing `tool_use` blocks.
+
+---
+
